  "text": "A bacterium enters your blood. Within seconds, it's dead. Here's exactly how. Phegocytosis. Phego means eat. Cite means sell. A phegocyte literally eats the pathogen. Step one, detection. The phegocyte recognizes chemicals released by the bacterium. It moves toward it. This is chemotaxis. Step two, attachment. The phegocytes membrane receptors bind to antigens on the bacterium's surface. Step three, engulfment. The membrane extends pseudopods around the bacterium. It wraps around it completely. The bacterium is now trapped inside a vesicle called a phagosome. Step four, digestion. A lysosome fuses with the phagosome, forming a phagolisosome. The lysosome releases hydrolytic enzymes. These enzymes break down the bacterium into small molecules. Step five, absorption. Useful molecules are absorbed into the cytoplasm. Waste is expelled by exocytosis. But here's the exam trick. After digestion, the phegocyte presents the pathogen's antigens on its surface. It becomes an antigen-presenting cell. This triggers the adaptive immune response. B cells and T cells. Detection, attachment, engulfment, digestion, antigen presentation. Know all five steps. That's your full marks.",
